<html><head><meta http-equiv="Content-Type" content="text/html; charset=utf-8" /><meta http-equiv="Content-Style-Type" content="text/css" /><meta name="generator" content="Aspose.Words for .NET 13.4.0.0" /><title>DDB0165</title></head><body><div><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:'Gill Sans MT'; font-size:12pt; font-weight:bold">Gambling Commission</span><span style="font-family:'Gill Sans MT'; font-size:12pt; font-weight:bold"> – Written evidence</span></p><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 10pt"><span style="font-family:'Gill Sans MT'; font-size:12pt; font-weight:bold">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 10pt"><span style="font-family:'Gill Sans MT'; font-size:12pt; font-weight:bold">Introduction</span></p><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 10pt"><span style="font-family:'Gill Sans MT'; font-size:12pt">The Gambling Commission (the Commission) welcomes this opportunity to contribute to the pre-legislative scrutiny of the draft Deregulation Bill. The Commission’s submission is solely in relation to the sections relating to non-economic regulators and the exercise of their functions.</span></p><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 10pt"><span style="font-family:'Gill Sans MT'; font-size:12pt; font-weight:bold">Commission’s response</span></p><ol type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:'Gill Sans MT'; font-size:12pt; margin:0pt 0pt 10pt 14pt; padding-left:4pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:'Gill Sans MT'; font-size:12pt">The Commission broadly welcomes the proposals contained in the Bill in requiring non economic regulators to have regard to the desirability of promoting economic growth. More specifically (at s58) to ensure that:</span></li></ol><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 10pt 54pt; text-indent:-18pt"><span style="font-family:'Gill Sans MT'; font-size:12pt">(a)</span><span style="font:7.0pt 'Times New Roman'">&#xa0;&#xa0; </span><span style="font-family:'Gill Sans MT'; font-size:12pt">regulatory action is only taken when it is needed </span></p><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 10pt 54pt; text-indent:-18pt"><span style="font-family:'Gill Sans MT'; font-size:12pt">(b)</span><span style="font:7.0pt 'Times New Roman'">&#xa0;&#xa0; </span><span style="font-family:'Gill Sans MT'; font-size:12pt">any action is proportionate </span></p><ol start="2" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:'Gill Sans MT'; font-size:12pt; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 14pt; padding-left:4pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:'Gill Sans MT'; font-size:12pt">The Gambling Commission is required by statute to permit gambling insofar as reasonably consistent with the licensing objectives of keeping crime  out of gambling; ensuring that it is  fair and open; and that children and the vulnerable are protected. (Broadly speaking the same requirement is placed on local authorities.)</span></li></ol><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 18pt"><span style="font-family:'Gill Sans MT'; font-size:12pt"> </span><span style="font-family:'Gill Sans MT'; font-size:12pt">              </span></p><ol start="3" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:'Gill Sans MT'; font-size:12pt; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 14pt; padding-left:4pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:'Gill Sans MT'; font-size:12pt">The Commission was created as a regulator based on the Hampton principles and the </span><span style="font-family:'Gill Sans MT'; font-size:12pt">Macrory</span><span style="font-family:'Gill Sans MT'; font-size:12pt"> characteristics of better regulation. An implementation review in 2009 recognised how far this approach had been successfully embedded within the way the Commission regulates and we continue to work to improve our performance in line with those standards. Parts (a) and (b) of s58 are integral to our approach.</span></li></ol><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 36pt"><span style="font-family:'Gill Sans MT'; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><ol start="4" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:'Gill Sans MT'; font-size:12pt; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 14pt; padding-left:4pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:'Gill Sans MT'; font-size:12pt">A practical manifestation of our position was demonstrated in the changes made to our fees structure in 2012 which removed potential barriers to business expansion and economic growth and reduced fees for most (non-remote) operators.</span></li></ol><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 36pt"><span style="font-family:'Gill Sans MT'; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><ol start="5" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:'Gill Sans MT'; font-size:12pt; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 14pt; padding-left:4pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:'Gill Sans MT'; font-size:12pt">The Committee will be aware that as a part of the suite of measures being introduced by BIS there is an amended Regulators Compliance Code and the (voluntary) Assessment of Regulatory Impact (ARI) which the Commission has agreed to adopt. Each of these measures, which the Commission supports, may also have an unintended consequence. As we are currently financed by means of fees charged on operators for their licenses, depending on size and type, any increase in resource required, would result in an impact on regulatory fees (the cost to the industry).</span></li></ol><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 36pt"><span style="font-family:'Gill Sans MT'; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><ol start="6" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:'Gill Sans MT'; font-size:12pt; margin:0pt 0pt 10pt 14pt; padding-left:4pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:'Gill Sans MT'; font-size:12pt">Our concern with the draft Bill is not the principles that it contains but rather some potential unintended consequences and risks which we set out below:</span></li></ol><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 10pt 53.85pt; text-indent:-17.85pt"><span style="font-family:'Gill Sans MT'; font-size:12pt">(a)</span><span style="font:7.0pt 'Times New Roman'">&#xa0;&#xa0; </span><span style="font-family:'Gill Sans MT'; font-size:12pt">The conditions for economic growth (in the gambling industry) require public confidence in our role as an independent regulator. Fundamental to public confidence, and therefore growth, is that the regulator is, and is seen to be, wholly independent, impartial and objective. While we do not believe the current wording of the draft legislation should impair our objectivity, there is a risk that the concept of the desirability of economic growth becomes confused or </span><span style="font-family:'Gill Sans MT'; font-size:12pt">conflated with the promotion of the commercial interests of specific economic sectors. If it appears to the public that it is any part of the Commission’s role to promote the industry - as opposed to permitting the industry to promote itself and grow so far as is compatible with consumer protection, the likely outcome is a reduction in public confidence and a consequent reduction in the public acceptance of gambling as a main stream leisure </span><span style="font-family:'Gill Sans MT'; font-size:12pt">acitivity</span><span style="font-family:'Gill Sans MT'; font-size:12pt">. This is a point made very clearly by the Culture, Media and Sport Select Committee in its report </span><span style="font-family:'Gill Sans MT'; font-size:12pt; font-style:italic">The Gambling Act 2005: A bet worth taking?</span><span style="font-family:'Gill Sans MT'; font-size:12pt">, 24 July 2012).  </span></p><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 10pt 53.85pt; text-indent:-17.85pt"><span style="font-family:'Gill Sans MT'; font-size:12pt">(b)</span><span style="font:7.0pt 'Times New Roman'">&#xa0;&#xa0; </span><span style="font-family:'Gill Sans MT'; font-size:12pt">Should the manner in which economic growth is supported under section 58 be prescribed any further there is a risk that this would constrain flexibility to modify our approach according to the size and type of business, resulting in the stated objectives not being met. Any attempt to be prescriptive about how to implement section 58 would seem to require quite complex guidance which would need to address size, scale, </span><span style="font-family:'Gill Sans MT'; font-size:12pt">geography</span><span style="font-family:'Gill Sans MT'; font-size:12pt"> and business type.</span></p><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 10pt 53.85pt; text-indent:-17.85pt"><span style="font-family:'Gill Sans MT'; font-size:12pt">(c)</span><span style="font:7.0pt 'Times New Roman'">&#xa0;&#xa0; </span><span style="font-family:'Gill Sans MT'; font-size:12pt">Specification could also inhibit our ability to ‘nip in the bud’ or move rapidly to deter operators from introducing products or behaving in ways that could harm consumers. In other words attempting to enshrine the principles in section 58 in process risks reducing our ability to act flexibly when we identify novel and contentious regulatory issues.   In turn this risks both the continued prosperity of compliant responsible operators undercut by sharp practice and also undermining public confidence in the industry  </span></p><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 10pt 53.85pt; text-indent:-17.85pt"><span style="font-family:'Gill Sans MT'; font-size:12pt">(d)</span><span style="font:7.0pt 'Times New Roman'">&#xa0;&#xa0; </span><span style="font-family:'Gill Sans MT'; font-size:12pt">Any accompanying guidance to the growth duty will be important. It is absolutely right, and helps develop better policy, for the industry to have a real input into determining the economic impact of any regulatory change; to be clear how that should be done; and to have some assurance their views are taken into account. But the reform measure designed to reduce burdens on industry and foster economic growth may have the unintended consequence of regulator and parts of industry expending time and money on unproductive and costly delaying tactics if the guidance does not encourage speedy and transparent decision making with the least possible procedural overhead. Otherwise the less responsible or competing </span><span style="font-family:'Gill Sans MT'; font-size:12pt">sectoral</span><span style="font-family:'Gill Sans MT'; font-size:12pt"> interests may be tempted to use it as a tool to block or delay changes in regulation which is essential to protect the public, for example blocking a loophole or dealing with an emerging problem. </span></p><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 10pt 53.85pt; text-indent:-17.85pt"><span style="font-family:'Gill Sans MT'; font-size:12pt">(e)</span><span style="font:7.0pt 'Times New Roman'">&#xa0;&#xa0; </span><span style="font-family:'Gill Sans MT'; font-size:12pt">In our view transparent decision making following genuine consultation to expose the issues involved, combined with the improved impact assessment for major changes proposed in the parallel ARI proposals and a better understanding of how growth is best fostered are sufficient to achieve the objectives Government has set. </span></p><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">&#xa0;</span><img src="data:image/png;base64," width="299" height="119" alt="" style="margin-left:255.9pt; margin-top:0.4pt; position:absolute; z-index:0" /></p><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:'Gill Sans MT'; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:'Gill Sans MT'; font-size:12pt">16 September 2013</span></p><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">&#xa0;</span></p></div></body></html>